  1. Use the Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test to check the stationarity.

bb) Next, Use log transformation and plot the series. Comment. Do you see any difference with the original fluctuations?

library(tseries)
adf.test(CL$CL.Adjusted)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  CL$CL.Adjusted
## Dickey-Fuller = -3.2609, Lag order = 17, p-value = 0.07734
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
#Since the value of Crude oil's adjusted price is just above 0.05,we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

#This means the time series is non-stationary. In other words, it has some time-dependent structure and does not have constant variance over time.

plot(log(CL$CL.Adjusted))

#The plot of log transformed data follows the same trend but the fluctuations seem smoother
  1. Get the ACF plot of the log transformed data. What can you say about the stationarity
adf.test(log(CL$CL.Adjusted))
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  log(CL$CL.Adjusted)
## Dickey-Fuller = -3.5606, Lag order = 17, p-value = 0.03641
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
#The value of p is less than 0.05 which means that the log transformed data is stationary

Problem 2

(i). Simulate MA(1), AR(3) and ARMA(3,1) with your preference of coefficients. Compare the ACF and PACF plots for MA(1), AR(3) and ARMA(3,1). What can you conclude from the graphs.

set.seed(100)
ar3.sim1 = arima.sim(list(order =c(3,0,0), ar=c(0.5, 0.5,-0.5)), n = 200)
ma1.sim1 = arima.sim(list(order =c(0,0,1), ma=c(0.5)), n = 200)
ar3ma1.sim1 = arima.sim(list(order =c(3,0,1), ar=c(0.5, 0.5, -0.5), ma=c(-0.5)), n = 200)

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
acf(ar3.sim1, lwd = 3)
acf(ma1.sim1, lwd = 3)
acf(ar3ma1.sim1, lwd = 3)

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
pacf(ar3.sim1, lwd = 3)
pacf(ma1.sim1, lwd = 3)
pacf(ar3ma1.sim1, lwd = 3)

#From the acf plots, it it clear that the acf for AR(3) and MA(1) tails to 0 whereas it remains constant for ARMA(3,1)
#From the pacf plots, it is clear that the model is most stationary for ARMA(3,1)
